Here are refined mitigation comments tailored for a Java + JSP + jQuery stack, using terminology reviewers expect for that ecosystem (servlets, filters, request validation, etc.):
1) CWE-829 – Unrecognized CSP Directive
Mitigation Comment:
This finding is a false positive. The application defines a Content Security Policy (CSP) header that includes the directive:
require-trusted-types-for 'script'
This is a valid modern CSP directive used to enforce Trusted Types in supported browsers, preventing DOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) by restricting unsafe script injection through JavaScript (including jQuery DOM manipulation APIs).
In our Java/JSP application:
CSP headers are set via server-side configuration (Servlet Filter / HTTP response headers).
No dynamic inclusion of scripts from untrusted domains is performed.
All JavaScript resources are either locally hosted or explicitly whitelisted.
The Veracode scan flags this due to lack of support for newer CSP directives, not due to insecure behavior.
As confirmed with Veracode support, this is a scanner limitation. The directive strengthens client-side security and does not introduce risk. Therefore, this issue is a false positive.
2) CWE-352 – Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)
Mitigation Comment:
This finding is a false positive. The application implements standard and effective CSRF protection mechanisms consistent with Java web security best practices.
Implemented controls:
CSRF tokens are generated per session/request on the server side (Java backend).
Tokens are embedded in JSP pages (hidden form fields / meta tags).
All state-changing requests (POST/PUT/DELETE) include the CSRF token.
Server-side validation is enforced via filters/interceptors before request processing.
Requests with missing or invalid tokens are rejected.
jQuery integration:
CSRF tokens are automatically included in AJAX requests using jQuery (e.g., via $.ajaxSetup or request headers).
Regarding the scan result:
For invalid or tampered requests, the application returns an error message within an HTTP 200 OK response.
This is intentional application behavior for consistent UI handling and does not indicate successful processing.
No business logic execution or state change occurs when CSRF validation fails.
Additional safeguards:
Content Security Policy (CSP) is enabled.
Session management and input validation follow secure coding practices.
As confirmed with Veracode, the finding is triggered by response handling (HTTP status code) rather than an actual CSRF vulnerability. Since CSRF protections are properly implemented and enforced, this issue is a false positive.
